#compdef wireit
# =============================================================================
# wireit — Google's "Wireit upgrades your npm/pnpm/yarn scripts to
#          make them smarter and more efficient" — a TypeScript
#          build tool that wraps npm/yarn/pnpm scripts with
#          DEPENDENCY GRAPH RESOLUTION + INCREMENTAL EXECUTION +
#          CACHING.  Distinguishing from Make, Gulp, Grunt, Turbo,
#          Nx, and other JS build tools by:
#            - npm-SCRIPT-NATIVE — wireit doesn't replace
#              package.json scripts; it WRAPS them.  Adding
#              wireit involves editing `scripts` field + adding
#              a `wireit` field defining dependencies +
#              file-input-output tracking
#            - DEPENDENCY GRAPH from package.json — scripts can
#              declare `dependencies: ["build:lib", "build:tests"]`
#              and wireit resolves the DAG before execution
#            - INCREMENTAL EXECUTION via FILE-INPUT TRACKING —
#              each script declares `files: ["src/**/*.ts"]`
#              for inputs + `output: ["dist/**/*"]` for outputs;
#              wireit hashes file contents + skips re-execution
#              when nothing changed
#            - 3 CACHING BACKENDS via WIREIT_CACHE env var:
#                * local (default off-CI)  — .wireit/cache/ disk cache
#                * github (opt-in)         — GitHub Actions cache API
#                                            for cross-CI-run sharing
#                * none                     — disabled
#            - --watch FLAG with two strategies:
#                * event (default, fsnotify-style)
#                * poll (interval-based fallback)
#            - PERSISTENT SERVICES — scripts marked as services
#              (long-running like dev servers) integrate into
#              the dependency graph + restart when inputs change
#            - 3 FAILURE MODES via WIREIT_FAILURES env:
#                * no-new (default)  — fail-fast, no new scripts
#                                       after first failure
#                * continue           — keep going, collect all failures
#                * kill               — kill running scripts on first fail
#            - 4 AGENT-DETECTION modes — wireit auto-detects npm
#              vs nodeRun vs pnpm vs yarnClassic vs yarnBerry to
#              correctly forward args (each agent handles `--`
#              differently)
#            - PARALLEL EXECUTION via WIREIT_PARALLEL env (or
#              default to 2x CPU count)
#            - fast-glob FILE-PATTERN MATCHING — wireit uses
#              fast-glob internally for input/output file-pattern
#              resolution against the filesystem
#          Used by: TypeScript monorepos + Google-internal Node
#          projects + Lit (the Web Components library), Material
#          Web Components, and other Google-OSS Node projects.
#
# Author:  Google LLC (google organization on GitHub) — Google's
#          Lit team built wireit to manage Lit's own multi-package
#          build graph; the tool was extracted as a standalone
#          open-source utility.  Continuous development with
#          regular releases.  License: Apache-2.0.
# Source:  https://github.com/google/wireit
#          https://github.com/google/wireit/blob/main/src/cli.ts
#          https://github.com/google/wireit/blob/main/src/cli-options.ts
#          https://github.com/google/wireit/blob/main/src/util/glob.ts
# CLI:     bin/wireit.js → src/cli.ts → src/cli-options.ts —
#          wireit is invoked via `npm run <script>` / `yarn
#          <script>` / `pnpm <script>` and reads scriptName from
#          npm_lifecycle_event environment variable.  Only one
#          direct CLI flag: --watch.  All other options come from
#          WIREIT_* environment variables.
# Library: fast-glob (https://github.com/mrmlnc/fast-glob)
#          ("fast-glob" — Denis Malinochkin (mrmlnc on GitHub) —
#           released 2017 as "It's a very fast and efficient glob
#           library for Node.js".  Distinct from every previously-
#           documented Node library by being narrowly focused on
#           FAST FILESYSTEM GLOB PATTERN MATCHING:
#             1. STREAMING + SYNC + ASYNC APIs:
#                  fg(['**/*.ts', '!node_modules'])  // async Promise
#                  fg.sync(['**/*.ts'])              // synchronous
#                  fg.stream(['**/*.ts'])            // Node Readable
#             2. MICROMATCH-COMPATIBLE PATTERNS — supports
#                **/* (recursive directories), ?(...) (zero or one),
#                +(...) (one or more), @(...) (exactly one),
#                !(...) (negation), [...] (character classes),
#                {a,b} (alternation), all matching the
#                micromatch dialect
#             3. NEGATION via ! PREFIX — patterns prefixed with !
#                exclude matching paths; multiple negations
#                composable
#             4. CUSTOM OPTIONS via second-arg config:
#                  cwd, deep, followSymbolicLinks, dot, ignore,
#                  onlyDirectories, onlyFiles, markDirectories,
#                  caseSensitiveMatch, baseNameMatch, braceExpansion,
#                  extglob, globstar, objectMode, unique, suppressErrors,
#                  throwErrorOnBrokenSymbolicLink, fs, stats
#             5. PERFORMANCE OPTIMIZATIONS — fast-glob is BENCHMARK-
#                LEADING vs node-glob + globby + minimatch for
#                large directory trees; uses readdir streams + lazy
#                filtering + fast string matching
#             6. FOUNDATIONAL ECOSYSTEM POSITION — fast-glob is
#                the GLOB ENGINE BENEATH Vite + esbuild + Rollup +
#                Webpack + Turbopack + Parcel + Snowpack + tsc +
#                ESLint + Prettier + Stylelint + Jest + Vitest +
#                Mocha + and basically every Node.js build/test
#                tool that needs to find files
#             7. globby (Sindre Sorhus) BUILDS ON fast-glob —
#                globby's higher-level API wraps fast-glob with
#                gitignore + .gitignore support + auto-cwd
#                detection)
# License: Apache-2.0 (wireit); MIT (fast-glob)
# Status:  wireit — 6,411+ stars on google/wireit, used by Lit +
#          Material Web Components + many Google-OSS Node projects;
#          fast-glob — 2,814+ stars on mrmlnc/fast-glob, ~400M
#          weekly npm downloads (TOP-20 npm package by weekly
#          volume), foundational dependency of Vite (66k stars) +
#          esbuild (38k) + Rollup (25k) + Vitest (12k) + globby
#          (Sindre Sorhus, builds on fast-glob) + ESLint + Prettier
#          + Stylelint + Jest + tsup + tsx + 10,000+ Node.js
#          build/test tools.
#
