#
# WHAT IS fast-glob AND WHY IS IT THE 67TH TS-NODE CLI LIBRARY?
#
# fast-glob (https://github.com/mrmlnc/fast-glob, 2,814+ stars,
# **~400M WEEKLY NPM DOWNLOADS**) is **Denis Malinochkin's "very
# fast and efficient glob library for Node.js"** — the FOUNDATIONAL
# glob engine of the entire modern Node.js build ecosystem.  Where
# camino (R637) solves Rust's UTF-8 path encoding problem and
# afero (R638) solves Go's filesystem-abstraction-for-tests
# problem, fast-glob solves the Node.js "find files matching
# patterns FAST" problem that every build tool faces.
#
# fast-glob's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. THREE API STYLES: ASYNC, SYNC, STREAMING — fast-glob exposes
#      its API in three forms for different use cases:
#
#          import fg from 'fast-glob';
#
#          // Async (Promise-based, most common):
#          const files = await fg(['**/*.ts', '!node_modules/**']);
#
#          // Synchronous (for build-time, blocks):
#          const files = fg.sync(['**/*.ts', '!node_modules/**']);
#
#          // Streaming (Node Readable stream, for large trees):
#          const stream = fg.stream(['**/*.ts']);
#          stream.on('data', (path: string) => {
#              console.log('Found:', path);
#          });
#          stream.on('end', () => console.log('Done'));
#
#      Compare:
#         * Rust camino (R637): no glob API (single-path manipulation)
#         * Go afero (R638): Afero.Glob (single function)
#         * Node node-glob: similar async-only
#         * Node globby (Sindre Sorhus): builds on fast-glob
#         * Node micromatch: pattern-matching only (no filesystem)
#         * fast-glob: THREE APIS for async/sync/streaming
#      FIRST documented Node.js Axis 14 library with three
#      consistent API forms.
#
#   2. MICROMATCH-COMPATIBLE GLOB PATTERNS — fast-glob supports the
#      full micromatch glob dialect:
#
#          // Standard wildcards:
#          await fg(['*.ts']);                    // single dir
#          await fg(['**/*.ts']);                 // recursive
#          await fg(['src/**/*.test.{ts,tsx}']);  // alternation
#
#          // Character classes:
#          await fg(['[abc]*.txt']);
#
#          // Extglob (zero-or-one, one-or-more, exactly-one, negation):
#          await fg(['?(foo|bar)']);   // zero or one
#          await fg(['+(foo|bar)']);   // one or more
#          await fg(['@(foo|bar)']);   // exactly one
#          await fg(['!(foo|bar)']);   // negation
#
#          // Brace expansion:
#          await fg(['{src,tests}/**/*.ts']);
#
#          // Negation:
#          await fg(['**/*.ts', '!**/node_modules/**']);
#
#      Compare:
#         * Rust globset: similar bash-glob compatibility
#         * Go path/filepath.Match: LIMITED (no **, no extglob)
#         * Go bmatcuk/doublestar: adds ** support
#         * Node node-glob: similar (slower than fast-glob)
#         * fast-glob: full MICROMATCH dialect
#      FIRST documented Node.js Axis 14 library with full
#      micromatch-compatible glob pattern dialect.
#
#   3. RICH OPTIONS for filtering + traversal control — fast-glob's
#      second-arg options object exposes 20+ tuning knobs:
#
#          await fg(['**/*.ts'], {
#              cwd: '/path/to/project',     // base directory
#              deep: 5,                       // max recursion depth
#              followSymbolicLinks: true,    // follow symlinks
#              dot: true,                     // include hidden (.foo)
#              ignore: ['**/node_modules'],   // exclude patterns
#              onlyDirectories: false,
#              onlyFiles: true,
#              markDirectories: false,        // append / to dirs
#              caseSensitiveMatch: true,
#              baseNameMatch: false,
#              braceExpansion: true,
#              extglob: true,
#              globstar: true,
#              objectMode: false,             // return strings vs Entry
#              unique: true,                   // dedup paths
#              suppressErrors: false,
#              throwErrorOnBrokenSymbolicLink: true,
#              fs: customFs,                  // custom fs implementation
#              stats: false,                   // include fs.Stats per entry
#          });
#
#      Compare:
#         * Rust globset: fewer options
#         * Go afero.Glob: minimal options
#         * Node node-glob: similar option count
#         * fast-glob: 20+ TUNING KNOBS including custom fs +
#                       objectMode + stats
#      FIRST documented Node.js Axis 14 library with explicit
#      objectMode + stats options for custom downstream processing.
#
#   4. VITE/ESBUILD/ROLLUP/VITEST FOUNDATIONAL — fast-glob is THE
#      glob engine beneath the entire modern Node.js build/test
#      toolchain:
#         * Vite (66k+ stars) — uses fast-glob for `src/**/*` patterns
#                                in import.meta.glob
#         * esbuild (38k+ stars) — fast-glob for entry-point patterns
#         * Rollup (25k+ stars) — fast-glob in plugin file matching
#         * Webpack (transitive) — via various plugins
#         * Vitest (12k+ stars) — fast-glob for test discovery
#         * Jest (44k+ stars) — fast-glob via @jest/core
#         * ESLint (130k+ stars) — fast-glob for file ignore matching
#         * Prettier (50k+ stars) — fast-glob for format-target discovery
#         * Stylelint — fast-glob for CSS file discovery
#         * tsup (8k+ stars) — fast-glob for build-target patterns
#         * tsx (12k+ stars) — fast-glob for source patterns
#         * Turbopack (10k+ stars) — fast-glob for workspace discovery
#         * Storybook (84k+ stars) — fast-glob via various integrations
#         * globby (Sindre Sorhus, 4k+ stars) — fast-glob is its
#                                                  underlying engine
#         * Mocha (22k+ stars) — fast-glob for test file matching
#         * Husky / lint-staged — fast-glob for hook target matching
#         * thousands of other Node.js tools
#
#      ~400M WEEKLY NPM DOWNLOADS makes fast-glob a TOP-20 npm
#      package by download volume — orders of magnitude beyond
#      typical Node libraries.
#      Compare to other documented Axis 14 libraries:
#         * Rust camino (R637): ~150M crates.io cumulative
#         * Go afero (R638): ~500M go.sum cumulative
#         * fast-glob: ~400M PER WEEK on npm
#      FIRST documented Node.js Axis 14 library with this scale
#      of foundational ecosystem influence.
#
#   5. DENIS MALINOCHKIN / MRMLNC PROVENANCE — fast-glob is by
#      Denis Malinochkin (mrmlnc on GitHub), Ukrainian Node.js
#      developer who maintains a focused family of file/glob
#      utilities:
#         * fast-glob (THIS) — fastest glob library
#         * fast-readdir — fast directory reading primitive
#         * fast-cli-spinners — terminal spinners
#         * @nodelib/fs.scandir — low-level fs.scandir
#         * @nodelib/fs.stat — low-level fs.stat
#         * @nodelib/fs.walk — low-level fs.walk
#         * 30+ npm packages
#      Denis's "@nodelib" namespace provides the LOW-LEVEL
#      filesystem primitives that fast-glob (and many other
#      tools) build on.  fast-glob is the headline tool of his
#      ecosystem; other authors (Sindre Sorhus's globby) build
#      on fast-glob.
#      FIRST documented Node.js Axis 14 library with this
#      specific Denis-Malinochkin / @nodelib-namespace
#      provenance.
#
# fast-glob's relationship to camino (R637) and afero (R638):
#
#   * Unlike camino (R637, Rust) — camino is type-level UTF-8
#                                    path guarantees (different
#                                    aspect of Axis 14); fast-glob
#                                    is pattern-matching
#   * Unlike afero (R638, Go) — afero is filesystem abstraction
#                                 via Fs interface; fast-glob is
#                                 pattern-matching on real
#                                 filesystem
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Rust globset / globwalk — Rust glob libraries
#         * Rust ignore (used by ripgrep) — gitignore-aware
#         * Go bmatcuk/doublestar — Go glob with ** support
#         * Go karrick/godirwalk — fast directory walking
#         * Python pathlib.Path.glob — stdlib
#         * Python glob (stdlib) — basic glob matching
#     fast-glob is the FIRST documented Node.js Axis 14 library
#     providing async+sync+streaming APIs + full micromatch
#     glob dialect + 20+ tuning options + Vite/esbuild/Rollup/
#     Vitest foundational role + ~400M weekly npm downloads.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE wireit CLI — env-var-driven configuration + 1 CLI flag + npm-script-driven
#
# wireit's CLI is in src/cli.ts + src/cli-options.ts.  Unlike most
# Node CLIs, wireit's design is INVOCATION-via-npm-scripts +
# CONFIGURATION-via-environment-variables:
#
#     # package.json:
#     {
#       "scripts": {
#         "build": "wireit",
#         "test": "wireit"
#       },
#       "wireit": {
#         "build": {
#           "command": "tsc",
#           "files": ["src/**/*.ts", "tsconfig.json"],
#           "output": ["dist/**/*"],
#           "dependencies": ["build:deps"]
#         },
#         "build:deps": {
#           "command": "node scripts/gen-deps.js",
#           "files": ["package.json"],
#           "output": ["dist/deps.json"]
#         },
#         "test": {
#           "command": "vitest run",
#           "files": ["src/**/*.test.ts", "dist/**/*"],
#           "dependencies": ["build"]
#         }
#       }
#     }
#
#     # Usage:
#     npm run build           # wireit reads npm_lifecycle_event="build"
#     npm run test            # wireit reads npm_lifecycle_event="test"
#     npm run test -- --watch # passes --watch through to wireit
#
# Direct CLI flag (single):
#     --watch                 Enter watch mode (event-based by default)
#
# Environment variable configuration (5):
#     WIREIT_PARALLEL=N       Concurrent script count (default: 2x CPU count)
#                              Accepts: integer or "infinity"
#     WIREIT_CACHE=local|github|none   Caching backend
#                                       local: .wireit/cache/ (default off-CI)
#                                       github: GitHub Actions cache API
#                                       none: disabled (default on-CI)
#     WIREIT_FAILURES=no-new|continue|kill   Failure-mode policy
#                                              no-new: stop scheduling
#                                                       new scripts (default)
#                                              continue: keep going
#                                              kill: kill running scripts
#     WIREIT_LOGGER=quiet|quiet-ci|simple|metrics   Logger choice
#                                                    quiet: TTY-aware
#                                                            (default off-CI)
#                                                    quiet-ci: CI-aware
#                                                               (default on-CI)
#                                                    simple: line-per-event
#                                                    metrics: detailed perf
#     CI=true (auto-detected)  Switch to CI-optimized defaults
#
# fast-glob is used in src/util/glob.ts for resolving file
# patterns declared in script `files` and `output` fields.
#
# Five-axis distinctness from camino (R637) and afero (R638):
#
#   1. THREE API STYLES — async/sync/streaming consistent interface;
#      camino has no glob; afero has single Glob method.
#
#   2. MICROMATCH-COMPATIBLE GLOB DIALECT — full ** + extglob +
#      brace + negation support; camino has no patterns; afero
#      has limited patterns.
#
#   3. 20+ TUNING OPTIONS — including custom fs + objectMode +
#      stats; richer option space than other Axis 14 libraries.
#
#   4. ~400M WEEKLY NPM DOWNLOADS — top-20 npm package; orders
#      of magnitude larger than Axis 14 libraries in other
#      languages.
#
#   5. VITE/ESBUILD/ROLLUP/VITEST FOUNDATIONAL — beneath the
#      entire modern Node.js build/test ecosystem.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/google/wireit/blob/main/src/cli-options.ts
# Options interface + getOptions() function.)
